WEBVTT

00:00:01.920 --> 00:00:07.760
<v Speaker 1>What was the to have that we use to go in the past?

00:00:08.599 --> 00:00:11.559
<v Speaker 1>Aber good.

00:00:11.559 --> 00:00:15.879
<v Speaker 1>How would you say I have cancelled?

00:00:15.879 --> 00:00:17.320
<v Speaker 1>I have cancelled

00:00:18.859 --> 00:00:20.619
<v Speaker 2>E cancelado.

00:00:20.619 --> 00:00:21.020
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:00:21.020 --> 00:00:22.619
<v Speaker 1>E cancelado.

00:00:22.619 --> 00:00:27.500
<v Speaker 1>And we said that the version of the verb that you get after haber, you can use it.

00:00:27.140 --> 00:00:31.140
<v Speaker 1>like an adjective as well in Spanish just as we do in English.

00:00:31.140 --> 00:00:34.340
<v Speaker 1>For example in English we could say it's cancelled.

00:00:34.340 --> 00:00:38.180
<v Speaker 1>We use the same version canceled that comes after aber.

00:00:38.180 --> 00:00:40.100
<v Speaker 1>So we can do the same in Spanish

00:00:40.020 --> 00:00:42.660
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say it is cancelled?

00:00:42.660 --> 00:00:51.380
<v Speaker 1>And I remind you that the adjectives that we form in this way tend to go with a star, only with a few exceptions that are more flexible.

00:00:51.380 --> 00:00:53.060
<v Speaker 1>So it is cancelled

00:00:53.920 --> 00:00:55.440
<v Speaker 2>Está cancelado.

00:00:56.880 --> 00:01:00.240
<v Speaker 1>What if we meant la fiesta, the party?

00:01:00.880 --> 00:01:02.320
<v Speaker 2>Está cancelada.

00:01:02.320 --> 00:01:02.880
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:04.560 --> 00:01:08.320
<v Speaker 1>Fiesta, by the way, is actually related to festival, festivity.

00:01:08.320 --> 00:01:13.440
<v Speaker 1>We can see the E splitting between festival and fiesta.

00:01:13.440 --> 00:01:15.600
<v Speaker 1>To complicate in Spanish.

00:01:15.600 --> 00:01:17.280
<v Speaker 1>What's complication?

00:01:18.240 --> 00:01:20.720
<v Speaker 2>Complicacion complicar.

00:01:20.720 --> 00:01:22.880
<v Speaker 1>Complicar with folding.

00:01:22.880 --> 00:01:24.400
<v Speaker 1>Complicar, good.

00:01:24.400 --> 00:01:32.400
<v Speaker 1>If you want to say it has got complicated, it has got complicated, how do you think you will say it?

00:01:33.700 --> 00:01:35.700
<v Speaker 2>Se ha complicado.

00:01:35.700 --> 00:01:36.259
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:36.259 --> 00:01:37.940
<v Speaker 1>Se ha complicado.

00:01:37.940 --> 00:01:39.380
<v Speaker 1>It has got complicated.

00:01:39.380 --> 00:01:41.460
<v Speaker 1>It has complicated itself, we would say.

00:01:41.460 --> 00:01:42.340
<v Speaker 1>Very good.

00:01:42.340 --> 00:01:45.140
<v Speaker 1>So the adjective complicated is

00:01:46.340 --> 00:01:47.299
<v Speaker 1>Complicado.

00:01:47.299 --> 00:01:48.100
<v Speaker 1>Complicado.

00:01:48.100 --> 00:01:48.579
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:48.579 --> 00:01:51.539
<v Speaker 1>So you can say it is complicated.

00:01:52.100 --> 00:01:53.460
<v Speaker 2>Es complicado.

00:01:53.460 --> 00:01:54.659
<v Speaker 1>Es complicado.

00:01:56.140 --> 00:01:57.340
<v Speaker 2>Está complicado.

00:01:58.780 --> 00:02:00.940
<v Speaker 1>Actually with this one you can use either.

00:02:00.940 --> 00:02:08.940
<v Speaker 1>There's to be a tendency to go with a estar with these types of adjectives, but with complicado you could say either.

00:02:08.540 --> 00:02:13.980
<v Speaker 1>Es complicado, está complicado, depending on what you are talking about.

00:02:13.980 --> 00:02:20.620
<v Speaker 1>You might feel more drawn to one or to the other, but most of the time they're gonna be interchangeable here.

00:02:20.620 --> 00:02:22.700
<v Speaker 1>We can also make structures like

00:02:23.280 --> 00:02:27.200
<v Speaker 1>Should have, could have, with this aber.

00:02:27.200 --> 00:02:29.120
<v Speaker 1>Let's start with should have.

00:02:29.120 --> 00:02:35.760
<v Speaker 1>Now should we take it from the verb to all, which also we use like must

00:02:36.020 --> 00:02:39.300
<v Speaker 1>And it's related to English debt.

00:02:39.300 --> 00:02:40.099
<v Speaker 2>Deber.

00:02:40.099 --> 00:02:41.540
<v Speaker 1>Deber, de bear.

00:02:41.540 --> 00:02:41.860
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:41.860 --> 00:02:44.260
<v Speaker 1>So deber is to owe or must.

00:02:44.260 --> 00:02:47.220
<v Speaker 1>And if you say would all, you get should.

00:02:47.220 --> 00:02:49.780
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say I should?

00:02:51.360 --> 00:02:51.760
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:51.760 --> 00:02:55.440
<v Speaker 1>So now we can say I should have cancelled.

00:02:55.440 --> 00:02:57.200
<v Speaker 1>And this have is to have.

00:02:57.200 --> 00:02:59.680
<v Speaker 1>I should to have cancelled.

00:03:03.560 --> 00:03:04.360
<v Speaker 1>Very good.

00:03:04.360 --> 00:03:05.720
<v Speaker 1>I should have cancelled.

00:03:07.640 --> 00:03:09.880
<v Speaker 1>I should have cancelled it.

00:03:10.680 --> 00:03:14.280
<v Speaker 2>Lo deberia haber cancelado.

00:03:14.280 --> 00:03:15.000
<v Speaker 1>Very good.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:18.120
<v Speaker 1>Lo debería haber cancelado.

00:03:18.120 --> 00:03:20.600
<v Speaker 1>Where else could that lo go there?

00:03:21.340 --> 00:03:25.020
<v Speaker 2>It's uh it's after the unchanged verb.

00:03:25.020 --> 00:03:28.780
<v Speaker 2>So deberia haber lo cancelado.

00:03:28.780 --> 00:03:31.900
<v Speaker 1>Yeah, deberia haberlo cancelado.

00:03:31.900 --> 00:03:32.780
<v Speaker 1>Very good

00:03:33.640 --> 00:03:35.800
<v Speaker 1>What was could?

00:03:35.800 --> 00:03:42.760
<v Speaker 1>So we take to be able and we say would be able to get this could, this could that refers to future.

00:03:42.760 --> 00:03:46.120
<v Speaker 1>So what is to be able related to power

00:03:46.860 --> 00:03:47.740
<v Speaker 2>Poder.

00:03:47.740 --> 00:03:48.940
<v Speaker 1>Poder, good.

00:03:48.940 --> 00:03:53.820
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say I would be able or I could?

00:03:53.820 --> 00:03:54.620
<v Speaker 2>Podería

00:03:55.040 --> 00:03:56.000
<v Speaker 1>Okay.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:56.880
<v Speaker 2>Podria.

00:03:56.880 --> 00:03:57.920
<v Speaker 1>Podría.

00:03:57.920 --> 00:04:01.520
<v Speaker 1>So you could say something like, I could have gone.

00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:02.640
<v Speaker 1>I could have gone.

00:04:02.640 --> 00:04:04.480
<v Speaker 1>What was to go?

00:04:04.940 --> 00:04:05.660
<v Speaker 1>Ir.

00:04:05.660 --> 00:04:06.140
<v Speaker 1>Ir.

00:04:06.140 --> 00:04:09.820
<v Speaker 1>And what was gone, the version of to go after Aber?

00:04:10.700 --> 00:04:11.980
<v Speaker 2>A ido.

00:04:11.980 --> 00:04:14.220
<v Speaker 1>I could have gone.

00:04:14.720 --> 00:04:17.120
<v Speaker 2>Podria haber ido.

00:04:17.120 --> 00:04:20.320
<v Speaker 1>Ah, podria haber ido.

00:04:20.640 --> 00:04:22.720
<v Speaker 1>We could have gone.

00:04:22.720 --> 00:04:24.480
<v Speaker 1>We could have gone.

00:04:25.020 --> 00:04:27.900
<v Speaker 2>Podriamos haber ido.

00:04:27.900 --> 00:04:28.539
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:04:28.539 --> 00:04:30.460
<v Speaker 1>Podriamos haber ido.

00:04:30.460 --> 00:04:31.099
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:04:31.099 --> 00:04:35.099
<v Speaker 1>So after Aber, any version of Aber, whether it's the two form

00:04:35.660 --> 00:04:43.340
<v Speaker 1>Aber whether it's a briya, any version of Aber is gonna have Ado or Ido with the following verb.

00:04:43.340 --> 00:04:49.500
<v Speaker 1>But some verbs are irregular and they don't form their version after Aber in this way

00:04:49.560 --> 00:04:53.960
<v Speaker 1>So to break, related to rupture in English, was romper.

00:04:53.960 --> 00:04:57.320
<v Speaker 1>Now this after aber is not rompido.

00:04:57.320 --> 00:04:59.720
<v Speaker 1>The rompido doesn't exist.

00:04:59.039 --> 00:05:00.080
<v Speaker 1>It's irregular.

00:05:00.080 --> 00:05:02.479
<v Speaker 1>After a bear it's roto.

00:05:02.479 --> 00:05:04.960
<v Speaker 1>R-O-T-O roto.

00:05:04.960 --> 00:05:08.240
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say I have broken it?

00:05:09.419 --> 00:05:11.659
<v Speaker 2>Lo E Roto.

00:05:11.659 --> 00:05:12.220
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:05:12.220 --> 00:05:13.819
<v Speaker 1>Lo E roto.

00:05:13.819 --> 00:05:14.940
<v Speaker 1>I have broken them

00:05:16.680 --> 00:05:18.920
<v Speaker 2>Los he roto.

00:05:18.920 --> 00:05:19.400
