00:05:29.460 --> 00:05:30.740
<v Speaker 1>Se arto.

00:05:30.740 --> 00:05:32.100
<v Speaker 1>It has broken itself.

00:05:32.100 --> 00:05:33.060
<v Speaker 1>It has broken.

00:05:33.060 --> 00:05:33.700
<v Speaker 1>Very good.

00:05:33.700 --> 00:05:35.460
<v Speaker 1>If you had just said a roto

00:05:35.960 --> 00:05:45.080
<v Speaker 1>I would understand he, she, it or you formal has or have broken and I would be waiting to hear what was broken.

00:05:44.840 --> 00:05:49.480
<v Speaker 1>So we have roto instead of rombillo, let's say.

00:05:49.480 --> 00:05:55.240
<v Speaker 1>Roto is the version of romber after aber, which means it will also count for the adjective.

00:05:55.240 --> 00:05:59.400
<v Speaker 1>So if you want to say it is broken, how would you say it?

00:06:00.220 --> 00:06:02.700
<v Speaker 2>Esta romp roto.

